<DOC><DOCNO> AP880914-0028 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-14-88 0240EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-APME-FOI     09-14 0263</FIRST><SECOND>PM-APME-FOI,0270</SECOND><HEAD>APME Chooses Six Newspapers As FOI Finalists</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Six newspapers have been selected as finalistsin the annual Freedom of Information Award competition sponsored bythe Associated Press Managing Editors association.   They are:   _The State, of Columbia, S.C., for its efforts in pioneeringapplication of the state's FOI law in an investigative series onthe University of South Carolina's refusal to disclose records ofdrug tests required of student athletes.   _The Dallas Morning News, for a six-month investigation andtwo-part series exposing how the judiciary in Texas excluded itselffrom federal and state open records and meetings laws, allowingjudges to operate outside public scrutiny.   _The Review Times, of Fostoria, Ohio, for its efforts to gainaccess to non-patient records of a community hospital association,involving lengthy court battles and ultimately legislative actionto revamp and restore Ohio's public records law.   _The Miami News, for accomplishments including preserving theright of the news media to conduct voter exit polls, winningrelease of documents sealed in a local murder case, the applicationof FOI in exposing flaws in a bail-bond system, and the use of FOIto document the wealth of the Archdiocese of Miami.   _The San Jose (Calif.) Mercury News for its investigative seriesexposing a behind-the-scenes relationship between the FairPolitical Practices Commission in California and the politicians itwas supposed to monitor.   _The Turlock (Calif.) Journal for its legal battles and effortsin reporting and educating the public during a confrontationbetween the newspaper and police department over access todocuments vital to public concern.</TEXT></DOC>